          "title": "2023 Project - Leaders in Teaching Ghana",
          "description": "The goal of Leaders in Teaching (LIT) Ghana is to improve the quality of teaching and learning in Ghanaian secondary education institutions (Senior High Schools (SHS), Senior High Technical Schools (SHTS) and Technical Institutes (TIs)) so that all young people have the 21<sup>st</sup> Century Skills and competencies needed for lifelong learning, employability and adult life. This goal will be achieved through five objectives:<ol>  <li>To improve the leadership and management of SHS, SHTS and TIs so      that School Boards and Leadership teams oversee effective learning-focused      institutions with School Improvement Plans which are conducting  robust learning assessments and using accurate,      timely and relevant data to inform decision-making. (LEAD- Schools)   To ensure effective      quality assurance and oversight of all SHS, SHTS, TIs and teacher      education institutions through      a performance      management and accountability system linking classroom, school, district,      regional and national levels. (LEAD- System)     To improve the quality      and relevance of pre-service and in-service teacher education so that all      teachers in SHS, SHTS and TIs are delivering the new secondary education      curriculum and adhering to the National Teachers' Standards.(TRAIN)   To attract, recruit and retain quality teachers for secondary      education institutions with a particular focus on the recruitment of women      and addressing staffing issues in rural areas.(RECRUIT)   To improve teacher motivation and elevate the status and respect      for the profession. (MOTIVATE) </li></ol> Transforming Teaching, Education &amp, Learning (T-TEL) is a Ghanaian not-for-profit organisation which adheres to world class standards in the provision of high quality technical advice and implementation support services to the Ministry of Education, Ghana Education Service and related agencies.  T-TEL will work with 14 institutional implementing partners to deliver the activities in LiT. These partners include tertiary education institutions, NGOs and the private sector. Each partners brings their own expertise to contribute towards LiT delivery. Their expertise will ensure that LiT is aligned with national and international best practice and underpinned by the highest quality evidence base possible. LiT will work to support 10 national government agencies, 16 Regional Education Offices (REOs) and 731 Senior High Schools (SHS), Senior High Technical Schools (SHTS) and Technical Institutes (TIs) to implement the ambitious national reforms set out in this proposal.  T-TEL, in partnership with the Ministry of Education and other national agencies and supported by the Mastercard Foundation, have spent the past twenty months working together on a program called Transforming Senior High School Education, Teaching &amp, Learning (T-SHEL) Phase One. This two-year program (ending in January 2023) has laid the foundations for transformative change in Ghana's secondary education system.  An effective foundation has been laid over the past twenty months but LiT is now urgently required to provide the technical and financial support needed if the Government of Ghana is to initiate and sustain a total transformation in secondary education. LiT will ensure that the new secondary education curriculum is understood and taught effectively across all schools, increasing the proportion of teachers meeting the National Teachers' Standards and ensuring that young people who complete secondary education have proficiency in the 21<sup>st</sup> Century Skills required to succeed in further studies and the world of work.   LiT Ghana will have a transformative impact on Ghana's secondary education system with a cumulative 2,300,000 secondary school students having participated in formal education underpinned by the new secondary education curriculum by the end of 2027. This is 2,300,000 young people (1,140,000 of whom are female) who will have been thr",
